{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638195"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17694"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17694"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10408"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72104"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10408"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57574"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10448"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24319"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24358"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72104"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe movement of endolymph within the inner ear is crucial for both hearing and balance. This fluid is produced in one specific location and flows through the membranous labyrinth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal flow of endolymph in the inner ear?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["From utricle to semicircular canals only","From stria vascularis to endolymphatic sac","From perilymphatic space to scala media","From endolymphatic sac to scala media","From scala tympani to scala vestibuli"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Estria vascularis actively secretes endolymph which flows to the endolymphatic sac\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the normal direction of endolymph flow through the membranous labyrinth of the inner ear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom utricle to semicircular canals only\u003C/strong\u003E describes an incomplete pathway, as endolymph flows throughout the entire membranous labyrinth system.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom perilymphatic space to scala media\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because perilymph and endolymph are separate fluid compartments that do not normally communicate.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom endolymphatic sac to scala media\u003C/strong\u003E describes flow in the opposite direction to normal physiological movement.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom scala tympani to scala vestibuli\u003C/strong\u003E describes the movement of perilymph rather than endolymph.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe stria vascularis maintains the unique ionic composition of endolymph, which is high in potassium and low in sodium. This composition is essential for proper function of the mechanotransduction channels in hair cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Endolymph flows from the stria vascularis through the scala media of the cochlea towards the endolymphatic sac.","The stria vascularis actively secretes potassium ions to maintain the high potassium concentration of endolymph.","The flow of endolymph is essential for normal inner ear function and balance."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57574"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17694"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57574"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:37:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:37:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10408"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72104"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4942"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:08+1